      "narration": "Drum Island. Nami burns with fever, the doctor is at the bottom of the mountain range, and a whiteout blizzard has erased all visibility. Chopper, carrying her, cannot see the path, the valley, or even three steps ahead — but through his hooves he can feel the slope directly under him: which direction tilts down, and how steeply. That feeling underfoot is a derivative, and it is the whole idea. The derivative of a function f at a point answers exactly one question: if I nudge the input a tiny bit, how much does the output move? Formally it is the limit as h goes to zero of f-of-w-plus-h minus f-of-w, all over h — rise over run, but taken at a single point rather than across a stretch. So if f-prime of w equals six, it means increase w by a tiny epsilon and f increases by about six epsilon; a negative derivative means the output moves opposite to the input; and a zero derivative means locally flat — you are at a valley bottom, a hilltop, or a plateau. You only need a handful of rules, each verifiable from the definition once: the power rule, that the derivative of w-to-the-n is n times w-to-the-n-minus-one; constants ride along, the derivative of c times f is c times f-prime; sums split, the derivative of f plus g is f-prime plus g-prime; and e-to-the-w and natural-log-w have derivatives e-to-the-w and one-over-w. That handful, plus the chain rule on the next slide, covers essentially all of deep learning. And here is the crucial framing: in machine learning the function we differentiate is always the loss. L-of-w is how wrong the model is when its parameter is w, and the derivative d-L-d-w tells us how the wrongness responds to each parameter — which is exactly the information we need to fix it. Chopper does not need a map of the mountain; he needs the slope under his feet, and that slope is d-L-d-w.",
